<TITLE> Power distribution gets Tk 1750 crore boost </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 23 (bdnews24.com)  The government approved a Tk 1750 crore injection for the much-maligned power distribution sector on Tuesday. A meeting of the Executive Committee of the National Economic Council approved seven projects in various sectors worth Tk 2,886 crore. Two involve development of the crucial power sector. A Tk 979 crore 'Central Zone Power Distribution Project' got the green light for reconstruction and renovation of substations, transformers and transmission lines of 12 Electric Supply Units at Mymensingh, Tangail, Jamalpur, Sherpur, Sunamganj, Moulavibazar and Sylhet. The meeting also approved Tk 770 crore for expansion of transmission lines as well as installing Grid Sub Centres at Dhaka, Narayanganj, Munshiganj, Chittagong, Comilla, Brahmanbaria and Khulna, for more efficient distribution. The last ECNEC meeting, on March 16, approved ten new peaking power plants, bids for four of which have already received the nod from the cabinet purchase committee, in an urgent attempt to address the national power crisis. Meanwhile, the ECNEC meeting on Tuesday, chaired by prime minister Shiekh Hasina, also approved Tk 684 core for a primary and mass education ministry project titled 'Reaching-Out to School Children'. Another Tk 215 crore was okayed to build the 'Sheikh Faziltunnesa Mujib Memorial Specialised Hospital and Nursing College' at Kashimpur of Gazipur District. A project of the environment ministry for poverty alleviation through social forestry received Tk 109 crore. Tk 100 crore project was approved for dredging of the Pashur river channel at Mongla seaport. The meeting also gave the go-ahead to an ICT ministry project for establishment of the South Asia Sub-regional Economic Cooperation Information Highway (Bangladesh Part). The Tk 29 crore project involves cooperation in the realm of ICT among Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Bhutan.
